{
  "local_port": 55870,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I deal with not being good enough for my parents?",
  "response": "Feeling like you're \"not good enough\" for your parents can be incredibly painful, but it's important to remember that your worth is not determined by their approval. Here are some steps that might help you navigate these feelings and build a healthier perspective:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Recognize That Their Expectations May Be Unrealistic**\n   - Sometimes parents have high or specific expectations based on their own experiences, fears, or desires. These expectations may not align with who you are or what you want for your life.\n   - Remind yourself that their standards are not always a reflection of your value.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Separate Their Opinions From Your Self-Worth**\n   - Your parents\u2019 approval does not define your worth. You are valuable simply because you exist, not because of what you achieve or how you live up to their expectations.\n   - Practice self-compassion and remind yourself that you are doing your best.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Communicate Your Feelings (If Safe and Appropriate)**\n   - If you feel comfortable, try having an honest conversation with your parents about how their expectations are affecting you. Use \u201cI\u201d statements, such as, \u201cI feel hurt when I don\u2019t meet your expectations.\u201d\n   - Keep in mind that they may not fully understand or change, but expressing yourself can still be empowering.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Set Boundaries**\n   - If their criticism or demands are overwhelming, it\u2019s okay to set boundaries. For example, you might say, \u201cI need to take a break from this conversation\u201d or \u201cI\u2019d prefer if we focus on what I\u2019m doing well.\u201d\n   - Boundaries protect your mental health and create space for you to grow.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Focus on Your Own Goals and Values**\n   - Take time to reflect on what matters most to you\u2014your passions, goals, and values. Pursue what makes you feel fulfilled, even if it doesn\u2019t align with your parents\u2019 expectations.\n   - Celebrate your own achievements, no matter how small they may seem.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Seek Support From Others**\n   - Surround yourself with people who appreciate and support you for who you are. Friends, mentors, or a therapist can provide validation and help you build confidence.\n   - A therapist, in particular, can help you process these feelings and develop strategies for coping.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Practice Self-Compassion**\n   - Be kind to yourself. It's normal to feel hurt when you don\u2019t meet someone else\u2019s expectations, but you deserve love and acceptance\u2014especially from yourself.\n   - Remind yourself that you are enough, just as you are.\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Consider Their Perspective**\n   - Sometimes, parents\u2019 criticism comes from a place of love or fear (e.g., wanting you to succeed or avoid hardship). While this doesn\u2019t excuse hurtful behavior, understanding their intentions might help you feel less personally targeted.\n\n---\n\n### 9. **Focus on What You Can Control**\n   - You can\u2019t control how your parents feel or behave, but you can control how you respond. Focus on your own growth, happiness, and well-being.\n\n---\n\n### 10. **Give It Time**\n   - As you grow and become more independent, your relationship with your parents may evolve. They may come to understand and accept your choices more fully over time.\n\n---\n\nRemember, you don\u2019t need to live up to anyone else\u2019s standards to be worthy of love and respect. You are enough, and your journey is valid. If the feelings persist or become overwhelming, consider reaching out to a mental health professional for additional support.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
